# Conditional Statements

Every useful program makes decisions. Think of an ATM: it checks your balance before dispensing cash. If the balance is sufficient, it dispenses. Otherwise it declines. An `if` statement lets your program do the same — run a block of code only when a condition is met.

## The if Statement

```javascript
const temperature = 38;
if (temperature > 37) {
    console.log("You have a fever.");
}
```

Two important syntax rules:
1. The condition goes inside **parentheses** `()`
2. The body goes inside **curly braces** `{}`

Unlike Python, JavaScript uses braces instead of indentation to define blocks.

## Adding else

```javascript
if (temperature > 37) {
    console.log("You have a fever.");
} else {
    console.log("Temperature is normal.");
}
```

The `else` block runs when the `if` condition is `false`. It has no condition of its own.

## Multiple Conditions with else if

```javascript
const score = 75;

if (score >= 90) {
    console.log("Grade: A");
} else if (score >= 80) {
    console.log("Grade: B");
} else if (score >= 70) {
    console.log("Grade: C");
} else {
    console.log("Grade: F");
}
```

JavaScript evaluates `else if` conditions top to bottom and executes only the first matching block. All remaining branches are skipped.

## One-Line if (no braces) — Use with Caution

Braces are technically optional when the body is a single statement, but omitting them is a common source of bugs. Always use braces.

## Truthy and Falsy in Conditions

Any value can be used as a condition — not just booleans:

```javascript
const username = "Rahul";
if (username) {
    console.log("Logged in as:", username);
}
// '' (empty string) would be falsy, so the block would not run
```

In the code example below, you will see a complete grade classifier using `if`, `else if`, and `else`.

codeExample.code:
// Exam Grade Classifier

const studentName = "Kavitha";
const score       = 83;

let grade, feedback;

if (score >= 90) {
    grade    = "A";
    feedback = "Outstanding! Keep it up.";
} else if (score >= 80) {
    grade    = "B";
    feedback = "Great work!";
} else if (score >= 70) {
    grade    = "C";
    feedback = "Good effort, room to improve.";
} else if (score >= 60) {
    grade    = "D";
    feedback = "Needs more practice.";
} else {
    grade    = "F";
    feedback = "Please seek extra help.";
}

console.log(`Student  : ${studentName}`);
console.log(`Score    : ${score}/100`);
console.log(`Grade    : ${grade}`);
console.log(`Feedback : ${feedback}`);

// Truthy / falsy in a condition
const promoCode = "SAVE20";
if (promoCode) {
    console.log(`Promo code applied: ${promoCode}`);
}

